nally a diminutive of <i>capa</i> ‘hood, cloak’, but later transferred to the sense ‘chapel, sanctuary’, with reference to the shrine at Tours where the cloak of Saint Martin was preserved as a relic."]},{"name":"Capelle","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): altered form of   Capell  .","French: topographic name for someone living by a chapel, from a regional variant of <i>chapelle</i> ‘chapel’ (compare   Chapelle   2), or a habitational name from any of several places named (La) Capelle. This surname is also found in Belgium (mainly Wallonia).","Dutch (also <b>Van Capelle</b>) and Flemish: habitational name for someone from any of various places called Capelle or Kapelle, from Middle Dutch <i>capelle</i> ‘chapel’."]},{"name":"Capel","meanings":["English: variant of   Capell  .","French: regional variant of   Chapel  , from a dialect diminutive of Old French <i>chape</i> ‘hooded cloak, cape, hood’, or ‘hat’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of cloaks or hats, or a nickname for a habitual wearer of a distinctive cloak or hat.","Catalan: old variant or Castilianized form of   Capell   ‘hat, hood’, a cognate of 2 above."]},{"name":"Cappel","meanings":["English: variant of   Capell  .","German and Dutch: variant of   Kappel   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. This surname is also found in northern France and in Alsace and Lorraine (compare 3 below).","French: in some cases also a variant of   Capel  . Compare 2 above."]},{"name":"Caple","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Capell  .","Americanized form of German   Kappel   or Dutch   Capel  ."]},{"name":"Caples","meanings":["English (Lancashire and West Rriding of Yorkshire): variant of   Capell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Probably an altered form of <b>Göbbels</b>, a patronymic from   Goebel  ."]},{"name":"Capwell","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): variant of <b>Capewell</b>, probably a hypercorrect form of   Capell 